      <!-- Section 1: The AEO Definition -->
      <section id="definition" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The AEO Definition</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Answer engine optimisation (AEO) is the work of formatting and marking up content so that answer engines — featured snippets, AI Overviews, voice assistants, and AI chatbots — can lift a clean, direct answer straight from your page.</strong>
          Unlike traditional search engine optimisation, which targets ranking position within a list of links, AEO targets selection as the answer itself — the content displayed directly to the user, with or without a click-through.
        </p>

        <p>
          The term emerged as Google began prioritising direct answers over link lists for informational queries. When a user types "what is the speed of light" into Google, the engine no longer simply returns ten blue links. It extracts the answer — 299,792 kilometres per second in a vacuum — and displays it above everything else. AEO is the discipline of ensuring that extraction happens from your content.
        </p>

        <p>
          As AI-powered search has accelerated, the scope of AEO has expanded. It now encompasses not only Google's featured snippets and AI Overviews, but also the LLM-powered platforms — Perplexity, Microsoft Copilot, ChatGPT — that generate responses by synthesising information from multiple web sources. Any interface that delivers answers rather than links is, by definition, an answer engine.
        </p>

        <p>
          For a fuller treatment of AEO principles, see the <a href="/answer-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">complete AEO guide</a>. For a glossary-style breakdown of the term alongside related concepts, see the <a href="/aeo-definition/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO definition page</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: What Is an Answer Engine? -->
